.\" Man page for hsh - Holberton simple_shell (still wiring things up)
.TH HSH 1 "April 2026" "holbertonschool-simple_shell" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
hsh \- small UNIX command-line interpreter
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B hsh
.PP
Whatever path you use to start it (say
.BR ./hsh )
shows up as
.BR argv[0]
when something goes wrong.
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B hsh
is our Holberton
.B simple_shell
project: a tiny shell in C. Right now we are mainly getting the repo in order (README, this page,
.BR AUTHORS ,
that kind of thing), but the idea is straightforward: read a line, break it into words, run the command. Built-ins stay in the parent; everything else gets
.BR fork (2)
/
.BR execve (2)
with the real environment, and we wait on the child before drawing another prompt. Bare names should eventually resolve through
.BR PATH ;
full paths work when you type them.
.PP
Interactive: stdin is a tty, so you get a prompt each time. Non-interactive: no prompt, and we stop at EOF on stdin.
.PP
Build instructions and compiler flags are in
.B README.md
at the repo root; check there before you assume anything about the build.
.SH "BUILT-IN COMMANDS"
.TP
.BR exit
Quit the shell. Extra arguments to
.B exit
are out of scope for what we are being graded on.
.TP
.BR env
Print the environment,
.B name=value
one line at a time.
.SH ENVIRONMENT
Same env the process started with gets handed to child processes via
.BR execve .
Lookups use
.BR PATH
when the user types a bare command name (no slashes in the path).
.SH "EXIT STATUS"
0 when the main loop finishes clean, including EOF on stdin.
.B exit
should leave with 0 for our scope.
.SH BUGS
No pipes, no redirects, no real quoting; do not expect this to behave like full
.BR sh .
We will tighten this section once the code catches up.
.SH "SEE ALSO"
.B README.md
for build notes;
.B AUTHORS
for who touched the repo.
.SH AUTHOR
Listed in
.B AUTHORS
in the project root.
